 Gordon Liu of The 36th Chamber of Shaolin fame headlines the 1982 Shaw Brothers actioner The Young Vagabond. The film follows the turbulent life of nobleman-turned-drunken master Beggar So, a member of the Ten Tigers of Guangdong and one of China's most storied martial arts folk heroes.    The Young Vagabond is directed by Lau Si Yu, whose relatively short silver-screen filmography (including New Tales of the Flying Fox and Look Out, Officer) is overshadowed by his influence as a television producer and director.
 As one of TVB's golden PDs, Lau created many television classics including Journey to the West, Dark Tales, Legend of the Condor Heroes, The Bund, and   The Legend of Master So starring Chow Yun Fat as Beggar So. Gordon Liu and Chow Yun Fat are only two of the many famous names to have stepped into So's tattered shoes; there's also Stephen Chow in King of Beggars, Donnie Yen in Heroes Among Heroes, and of course Simon Yuen in Drunken Master.
 The So and the Man, the two big martial arts families of Guangzhou, often clash over matters both big and small. Despite their families' bitter rivalry, So Chan (Gordon Liu) becomes great friends with Man Ji Hou, as well as Siu Ling and Ma Kwan. Coming from a well-off family, So lives a carefree and comfortable life, but everything changes when he gets accused of the murder of his own father.
 The Young Vagabond co-stars Johnny Wang, Guk Fung, Wong Yue, Kwan Hoi San, and Bak Biu.
